@node Main

   @{b}EasyAmiTCP v2.0@{ub}
   @{i}© Arne Seime, 1996@{ui}
   SHAREWARE

   Everybody who have tried to install TCP/IP on an Amiga know that
   it is very difficult and takes a lot of time. For you modem-users
   it is expensive too, so I wrote this little program.

   EasyAmiTCP is a Graphical User Interface to easy configure AmiTCP/IP
   for a normal PPP connection.

   NOTE:
   It is very important that you read the whole guide before you start
   messing around.

   EasyAmiTCP is written in Arexx and uses MuiRexx for its GUI.
   

   @{"    " link "Installation" 0} Installation
   @{"    " link "How2Use" 0} How to use?
   @{"    " link "Future" 0} Future
   @{"    " link "History" 0} History


@endnode

@node Installation

   @{b}Installasjon@{ub}

   To use EasyAmiTCP you should have done the following:

   Installed AmiTCP/IP _AND_ configured it this way:
   1) Select EXPERT USER
   2) Select CHANGE AMITCP/IP CONFIGURATION
   3) Just enter something and press OK until you are prompted for
   4) SELECT ONE OF THE FOLLOWING CONFIGURATION STYLES, then press
      PPP CONFIGURATION
   5) For the rest of the prompts, JUST CLICK CONTINUE & OK until
      you get to the main menu again.
   
   Installed MuiRexx (found on Aminet) and assigned it.

   PPP.device by Holger Kruse installed in DEVS:NETWORKS/, and if
   you have the key, put it in S:

   Also check that the file AMITCP:DB/AMITCP.CONFIG is as follows:

#
#	$Id: AmiTCP.config,v 4.3 1994/10/02 23:06:51 jraja Exp $
#
#	AmiTCP/IP configuration file. See documentation for usage.
#
#	Copyright © 1994 AmiTCP/IP Group,
#	                 Network Solutions Development Inc.
#	                 All rights reserved.
#
useloopback=YES
debugsana=NO
usens=SECOND
gateway=YES


@endnode

@node How2Use

   @{b}How to use?@{ub}


   EasyAmiTCP is simple in use, but it requires you to have some basic
   knowledges on using modems. Please consult the docs that follows
   AmiTCP and ppp.device for further information.

   Every time you start EasyAmiTCP it tries to read the old stored information,
   but sometimes it fails. Check that the assigns are done, and that the
   nescessary files exists.

   @{b}Default user@{ub}

   The name specified here have _NOTHING_ to do with the login name at you
   Internet-provider. It it, though, you "name" on internet.

   If you specify a login that does not exists, a new account will be created.
   You will be prompted for the new password.

   @{b}Real name@{ub}

   The name you want to use, not nescessary.

   @{b}User ID@{ub}

   I don't know how to use this correctly, so any value will do.

   @{b}Group ID@{ub}

   I don't know how to use this correctly, so any value will do.

   @{b}Home directory@{ub}

   This is your personal directory, where files will be stored.

   @{b}IP Address@{ub}

   Here you should specify you IP address, but if you have a dynamic
   connection (You get a new number every time you connect), you should
   set it to 0.0.0.0

   @{b}Netmask@{ub}

   The mask of you internet-providers computer.

   @{b}Nameserver IP@{ub}

   The address to the computer which "translates" the addresses to
   IP-numbers.

   @{b}Gateway@{ub}

   The IP of the computer you are calling, also called DNS.

   @{b}Domain suffix@{ub}

   The domain of the computer you are calling, i.e. bryggen.bgnett.no becomes
   bgnett.no

   @{b}Serial driver@{ub}

   The device you want to use with the modem. (Serial.device etc.)

   @{b}Unit@{ub}

   The unit you want to use. Should be 0 unless you have extra serial-ports.

   @{b}Baud Rate@{ub}

   The speed you want to operate at. 38400 is nice for 14400 modems.

   @{b}MTU@{ub}

   MaxTransferUnit, I'm not sure, consult the ppp.guide.

   @{b}Dialscript@{ub}

   The script that ppp.device uses to call the provider. Must be in
   AmiTCP: .

   Example of a dialscript:

ECHO ON
TIMEOUT 5000
SEND "ATZ"
WAIT "OK"
SEND "ATDT<phonenumber to provider>"
WAIT "CONNECT"
WAIT "login:"
SEND "<username>"
WAIT "assword:"
SEND "<passwd>"
DELAY 100

   @{b}Carrier Detect@{ub}
   @{b}CTS/RTS@{ub}
   @{b}No EOF mode@{ub}
   @{b}Use ODU@{ub}
   @{b}Shared mode@{ub}

   These are options for the ppp.device. If you dont know what they are
   used for, consult the ppp.guide.

   PPP.device includes a lot of other options, but as they are not of the
   importance of the included ones, I have not include them.
   If you are in the need for using them, use the config-script
   included with AmiTCP/IP.

   NOTE:
   EasyAmiTCP deletes other options that is not supported!

   @{b}Config@{ub}
   @{b}Exit@{ub}

   :)

@endnode

